<span id="freeTextContainer10921688148834468822">3 stars<br/><br/>I don&apos;t think I found this book as enjoyable as some others did, but I did find bites and pieces of it amusing and/or educational. <br/><br/>I definitely agree with one quote from the book however...<br/><br/>&quot;We may be fairly happy now, but there&apos;s always tomorrow and the prospect of a happier place, a happier life. We never fully commit. That, I think, is a dangerous thing. We can&apos;t love a place, or a person, if we always have one foot out the door.&quot;<br/><br/>I also liked this quote...<br/><br/>&quot;There is one simple question, </span>
  <span id="freeText10921688148834468822" style="display:none">3 stars<br /><br />I don't think I found this book as enjoyable as some others did, but I did find bites and pieces of it amusing and/or educational. <br /><br />I definitely agree with one quote from the book however...<br /><br />"We may be fairly happy now, but there's always tomorrow and the prospect of a happier place, a happier life. We never fully commit. That, I think, is a dangerous thing. We can't love a place, or a person, if we always have one foot out the door."<br /><br />I also liked this quote...<br /><br />"There is one simple question, the answer to which identifies your true home. That question is: 'Where do you want to die?'"<br /><br />A person's answer may not be the happiest place in the world - but most likely - will be home.</span>
