        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer719031457" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12501035330046288602">Being a cynic myself, I loved the title of the book. The author, an NPR correspondent, provides a humorous and witty account of his travels around the world in search of the happiest places in which people live. His goal was not to find what makes people happy but rather locating the geographic area where there appears to be an abundance of happiness. The author&apos;s witty sarcasm is better appreciated listening to the audio version. I found it a laugh out loud informative book.</span>
  <span id="freeText12501035330046288602" style="display:none">Being a cynic myself, I loved the title of the book. The author, an NPR correspondent, provides a humorous and witty account of his travels around the world in search of the happiest places in which people live. His goal was not to find what makes people happy but rather locating the geographic area where there appears to be an abundance of happiness. The author's witty sarcasm is better appreciated listening to the audio version. I found it a laugh out loud informative book.</span>
